"https://news.google.com/rss/search?q=atp+tennis","Stefanos Tsitsipas names the ATP player that he considers the greatest of all time over Novak Djokovic","https://www.thetennisgazette.com/news/stefanos-tsitsipas-names-the-atp-player-that-he-considers-the-greatest-of-all-time-over-novak-djokovic/","Thu, 12 Jun 2025 15:00:00 GMT","

Novak Djokovic is often considered the greatest tennis player of all time, but not by world number 26 Stefanos Tsitsipas. 

Djokovic is a record 24-time Grand Slam champion, winning nine of those major titles with Goran Ivanisevic as his coach.

The Serbian parted ways with the former Wimbledon champion last year, with Ivanisevic now coaching Tsitsipas.

While Djokovic and Tsitsipas now have that in common, the Greek has picked another player as his greatest player of all time.

As a result of winning more major titles than anyone else, Djokovic is often seen as the greatest player in history.

However, when speaking in a video at the Patrick Mouratoglou Tennis Academy, Tsitsipas revealed that he thinks that his greatest men's player of all time is Roger Federer.

Federer previously made a big claim about Tsitsipas, and now the two-time Grand Slam finalist has returned the favour claiming that not having the most major titles does not matter to him.

“My GOAT would be Roger Federer,” said Tsitsipas. “Obviously he doesn't have the most Grand Slam titles but – to me – it doesn't matter. To me, what matters is the effect that he has had on the world of tennis, not just on the world of tennis, but in global sports. 

“I would compare it to the effect of Michael Jordan and I feel lucky that I have had the opportunity to share the tennis court with him. 

“It was probably one of the most majestic experiences of my life, getting to step out on the court and play against him. I suddenly felt alive, even though he kicked my a** a few times.”

Djokovic has won more Grand Slam titles than both his former rivals, but it is Federer who has won the most ATP titles overall.

Tsitsipas played Federer four times before he retired in 2022, with their head-to-head level at two wins apiece.

However, the former world number three has a losing record against both Djokovic and Rafael Nadal.

Tsitsipas, whose girlfriend is Paula Badosa, followed up on his comments about Federer by naming his greatest women's player of all time.

The 26-year-old went on to name Serena Williams, who Tsitsipas has previously trained with.

“On the woman's side, I would say Serena Williams, what she has done is superb,” said Tsitsipas. 

“Her story is unique and I really look up to her and she has big charisma and also presence because I've spoken to her a few times and I've obviously practised with her, I feel like she really deserves that title.”

A post shared by Mouratoglou Tennis Academy (@mouratoglou_tennis_academy)

Tsitsipas is not the only person who has recently made this claim, with Chris Evert also calling Williams the greatest after ranking her top five.","{'href': 'https://www.thetennisgazette.com', 'title': 'The Tennis Gazette'}","tennis"
"https://news.google.com/rss/search?q=atp+tennis","German teenager Engel reaches first ATP Tour quarters in Stuttgart","https://sports.yahoo.com/article/german-teenager-engel-reaches-first-131754751.html","Thu, 12 Jun 2025 13:17:54 GMT","







Manage your account



...

German 17-year-old Justin Engel reached a quarter-final of an ATP Tour event for the first time in his young career.

He achieved the feat on Thursday at the Stuttgart Open with a 6-4, 6-4 win against seventh seeded American Alex Michelsen.

Engel broke Michelsen in the third game of each set, did not face a break point, and won all 31 points on his first serve en route to victory in 1 hour 17 minutes which he sealed with a service winner.

Wildcard entry Engel named his success ""unbelievable"" and admitted he had been ""very nervous"" before the match.

Playing in his first professional grass court event, he became the youngest player to reach an ATP quarter-final on this surface since Boris Becker's first triumph at Wimbledon 40 years ago.

""This is nice to hear,"" he said, adding that he ""simply wants to play tennis and have fun on court.""

Thursday's success over 35th ranked Michelsen was his first victory over a top 50 player, and he will rise in the rankings from a current 281st into the top 250.

Engel is among several talented German 17-year-olds. Diego Dedura has also started playing on the ATP Tour, while Niels McDonald and Max Schönhaus contested the junior final at the French Open on Saturday, with McDonald taking the trophy.

Germany's top player Alexander Zverev was set to play later Thursday against Frenchman Corentin Moutet in Stuttgart, which is one of the tune-up events for Wimbledon which starts on June 30.","{'href': 'https://sports.yahoo.com', 'title': 'Yahoo Sports'}","tennis"
