"https://news.google.com/rss/search?q=Psychic","7 Best Anime Characters With Psychic Powers","https://www.dualshockers.com/best-anime-characters-with-psychic-powers/","Thu, 12 Jun 2025 16:00:00 GMT","

The realm of anime has gifted us with some of the most extraordinary characters whose minds transcend the boundaries of ordinary human capability. From subtle telepaths who navigate the complexities of reading thoughts to powerhouses capable of reshaping entire landscapes with mere concentration, psychic abilities have become a fascinating cornerstone of supernatural storytelling.

Search bars do not lie, these most searched anime names keep autocomplete busy.

These characters don't just wield incredible powers, they carry the weight of abilities that often isolate them from normal society, forcing them to grapple with questions of morality, responsibility, and what it truly means to be human.

These seven characters have redefined what it means to possess psychic abilities, each leaving an indelible mark on their respective series and the hearts of viewers worldwide.



He can rewrite memories, teleport across countries, see through walls, and even destroy the planet if he ever felt like it, but all Kusuo Saiki really wants is to eat coffee jelly in peace.

The Disastrous Life of Saiki K. flips the entire psychic-powered anime genre on its head by making its most powerful character desperate to live an average life. Born with an arsenal of god-tier psychic abilities, Saiki wears limiters over his head to suppress his powers, not for safety, but so that he doesn't accidentally warp reality while trying to tie his shoes.

What makes Kusuo stand out isn't just the scale of his powers, but how meticulously the show breaks down their consequences. His x-ray vision ruins surprise birthday parties. His telepathy means he can't stop hearing people's thoughts. Even teleportation becomes a curse when he tries to skip social interaction and ends up in weirder situations.

Through his inner monologues, the anime builds him as more than just a gag character. He's deeply isolated, always pretending not to care, while quietly going out of his way to protect the friends who unknowingly drag him into chaos every day. He might be the strongest psychic in anime, but he's also the loneliest.



At first glance, Yuu's ability seems like a cheat code, he can possess someone's body for five seconds. But there's a catch: while doing so, his own body collapses, and more importantly, he can't use it without consequences.

Initially, Yuu abuses his power for selfish reasons, cheating on tests and showing off. But everything changes when he meets Nao Tomori and joins a school for psychic teens. From there, Charlotte unravels into something much darker. We learn that Yuu's ability isn't just possession, it's “plunder.” He permanently steals the powers of those he possesses, unknowingly stripping others of their identities.

Things spiral after a tragic loss sends him into a grief-fueled descent. In a near-insane state, he begins plundering abilities across the globe, making himself a ticking time bomb. By the end of the series, he holds the power of hundreds, including mind reading, pyrokinesis, time travel, and more, but in return, he forgets who he is.

Yuu's arc is painful and profound. He starts as a selfish teen and ends as a hollow shell of a boy who gave up everything to protect a world he can no longer even remember.



Anya doesn't fight in wars or blow up buildings with her psychic powers. She's not here to save the world, she just wants to help her pretend parents stay together.

Anya is a young telepath created through mysterious experiments by an unknown organization. She escapes the lab and is adopted by Loid Forger, a secret spy who needs a fake child to complete his undercover mission. What he doesn't know is that Anya can read minds, which makes for some of the most chaotic and heartwarming moments in the anime.

These 7 anime characters stand out not for their strength, but for how deeply they grow, shaped by choices and pain.

Unlike traditional psychic characters, Anya's powers are unpredictable and often hilariously misused. She tries to manipulate conversations by reading thoughts but ends up misinterpreting them. Her grades don't improve despite knowing answers. Her childish understanding of adult thoughts adds layers of comedy and tragedy, especially when she overhears fears of war, secrets of betrayal, or her parents' buried traumas.

Her small hands can't stop missiles, but her heart often holds the Forger family together. She's the glue that binds a spy, an assassin, and a troubled dog into something resembling a real home.



When he first appeared in My Hero Academia, Hitoshi Shinso wasn't taken seriously. He wasn't flashy, didn't have super strength or fire powers. But all it took was a single reply from his enemy, and the fight was over.

Shinso's quirk, Brainwashing allows him to control anyone who responds to his voice, but the moral implications of mind control have haunted him since childhood. Other students and adults instinctively label his quirk as villainous, creating a self-fulfilling prophecy that nearly drove him toward actual villainy.

Rather than give up, he learned how to fight smart. He uses voice modulators to mimic others and trick enemies into speaking. He develops physical skills to back up his quirk. And when given the chance to prove himself in the U.A. Joint Training arc, he doesn't just hold his own, he steals the spotlight.

What makes Shinso fascinating is how his psychic ability reflects the stigma around mind-control powers in hero societies. People fear his quirk. They see it as villainous. But Shinso wants to be a hero more than anything, and he's willing to fight tooth and nail to be seen as one.



In the Naruto universe, psychic powers aren't rare, but few use them with as much skill and depth as Ino Yamanaka.

Ino's signature technique, the Mind Transfer Jutsu, allows her to take control of a target's body by projecting her consciousness into them. But while it sounds simple, it leaves her body vulnerable and requires absolute precision, one mistake, and she's a sitting duck. Early on, this makes her more of a support shinobi, but by the time of Shippuden and Boruto, she becomes a key asset to the Allied Shinobi Forces and the Hidden Leaf's Intelligence Division.

She also inherits the Yamanaka clan's sensory techniques, letting her telepathically link entire squads, scan battlefields, and coordinate attacks in real time, turning the tide in major wars by sheer psychic coordination alone.

But Ino's power is never just about combat. She uses it to comfort dying comrades, maintain emotional connections, and even communicate across vast distances. Her psychic gifts are an extension of her emotional intelligence, something often overlooked in battle-heavy stories.



If there's a character who embodies destruction in the form of a small, green-haired woman with zero patience, it's Tatsumaki, also known as the “Tornado of Terror” from One Punch Man.

She's an S-Class Rank 2 hero, second only to Blast, and far above nearly everyone else in terms of sheer power. Her psychic ability, psychokinesis, lets her lift entire city blocks, generate force fields, fly, stop bullets mid-air, and flatten monsters with a flick of her finger. When she gets serious, the landscape suffers more than the enemy.

But what really defines Tatsumaki isn't her power, it's her fury. She's angry at incompetence, at weakness, and at anyone who underestimates her because of her height or age. Her brash personality masks a painful childhood, where she was imprisoned and experimented on until Blast himself rescued her. That trauma shaped her obsession with strength and her overprotectiveness toward her sister, Fubuki.



Shigeo Kageyama, known as “Mob,” is a quiet middle schooler from Mob Psycho 100, and arguably one of the most dangerous psychics in anime history.

Mob's powers are immeasurable. He can exorcise high-level spirits in seconds, crush buildings with his mind, and manipulate matter at the atomic level. But none of that defines him. What defines Mob is that he doesn't want to use these powers at all.

For Mob, psychic ability is a burden. From a young age, he realized that his powers could hurt people. So, he suppresses his emotions, avoids conflict, and trains physically so he won't have to rely on his gifts. His internal “emotion meter” counts upward during stress, and when it hits 100%, the explosion is devastating.

Each time Mob reaches that breaking point, we see different sides of his psyche: grief, rage, fear, acceptance. His journey isn't about mastering his powers, it's about understanding his emotions, learning to love himself, and connecting with others as an ordinary human.

