"https://news.google.com/rss/search?q=women's+us+soccer","Emma Hayes makes drastic decision for USWNT roster ahead of Women's World Cup","https://www.themirror.com/sport/soccer/emma-hayes-uswnt-world-cup-1205045","Thu, 12 Jun 2025 18:03:00 GMT","

With one eye on the 2027 FIFA Women's World Cup in Brazil, U.S. Women's National Team head coach Emma Hayes is planning to make some major changes to her roster.

Hayes recently teased changes ahead of their next game, and more details have now emerged. It comes after USMNT manager Mauricio Pochettino took notes from his USWNT counterpart

Having only recently played both China and Jamaica in friendlies, winning 3-0 and 4-0 respectively, Hayes' side will return to action on June 26 and 29 when they host the Republic of Ireland.

However, Hayes does not intend to call up a full-strength squad, in an aim to rest most of her European-based stars, allowing them a well-earned break.

“We have certainly taken a few different perspectives for this upcoming camp, and we've left out the vast majority of players that are playing in Europe, bar one, and that's Naomi Girma,” Hayes recently told ESPN.

“But the rest of those players have been playing non-stop last two years without a summer break, and we think this is the only opportunity that they will get a much-needed break, and it will give us the chance to play players that are playing domestically.”

Girma will return for her second consecutive camp, with injuries having limited her to just seven appearances since joining Chelsea at the end of January, when she became the first ever $1 million women's player.

Reflecting on her decision to rest her European stars, Hayes explained it came down to a mixture of “performance and medical” factors.

“We wound back from the World Cup two years ago, then the Olympics, and players from Emily Fox, Lindsay Horan, they have had no off-season over two years, and in Europe, players play for 10 and a half, 11 months, and with those tournaments and the way that they take place in the late summer in football calendar meant that they were literally getting a week's break and going back into a full 11-month season,” she said.

“So, this is the first opportunity that we, and the only one, for them to take a break between now and the World Cup in two years, and player welfare and rest and recovery are also important for these players.”

One player set to make her long-awaited return to the USWNT lineup at the upcoming camp will be Gotham FC's Rose Lavelle, having now recovered after undergoing surgery on her ankle in December.

“When it comes to Rose, she's been out just over six months, so very much hope that she will be with us in camp, and she's had, as she calls it, a very lengthy layoff,” Hayes explained.

“I don't think Rose, you know, makes a really good injured player. She's bored, senseless. I think she's really looking forward not just to get back for Gotham.

“I think it was great for her to make an appearance at the weekend, but we miss her at the national team, we miss her experience and very much looking forward to her coming back.”

As for Trinity Rodman, who opted to step away from soccer in April in order to focus all of her attention on managing an ongoing back issue, Hayes does not expect to see her in the upcoming camp. However, it seems the Washington Spirit star is nearing a return to action.

“I think with Trinity, I don't think we will see her back this camp, but I expect her to return playing for Washington Spirit in July at some point,” Hayes said. “But of course she has to feel that her back's in a place that she can move beyond the pain that she's carried for a period of time, but she's in great spirits, and I know we're moving in the right direction with Trin.

“Both club and country have been working hard to get her to this stage, and like I said, I expect her to return to the NWSL in July at some point.”

